    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "It appears that `plot -Am` plot by following the parallel first, then the meridian. `plot -Am` follows the parallel first, then the meridian. Should it not be the other way around? Based on https://docs.generic-mapping-tools.org/dev/plot.html#a; *Alternatively, add m to draw the line by first following a meridian, then a parallel. Or append p to start following a parallel, then a meridian.*\r\n\r\nI see that the modules `plot3d`, `grdmask`, `clip` and  `grdtrack` also has this option, but have not checked them. `sample1d` seems to be correct.\r\n\r\n```\r\ncat<<eof > test.gmt\r\n>\r\n5.53962564298\t71.272033721\t1\r\n6.30984353357\t71.4308039355\t2\r\n7.34727069584\t71.4156247566\t3\r\n7.9243956509\t71.1059801628\t4\r\n5.08609083753\t71.2631386067\t5\r\n5.53962564298\t71.272033721\t1\r\neof\r\n\r\ngmt begin blocky-line\r\n  gmt plot test.gmt -Ap -Wthicker,red -l\"plot -Ap\"+jTL\r\n  gmt plot test.gmt -l\"original\"\r\n  gmt sample1d -T10k -Ap test.gmt | gmt plot -l\"sample1d -Ap\" -Wblue\r\n  gmt sample1d -T10k -Am test.gmt | gmt plot -l\"sample1d -Am\" -Wgray\r\n  gmt plot -B0 -Sc0.4 -Ggreen -W test.gmt\r\n  gmt text test.gmt\r\ngmt end show\r\n\r\nrm test.gmt gmt.history\r\n```",
